ually brief durations, indicating that they were probably non-pyramidal cells. 7. ACh blocked the slow after-hyperpolarization (a.h.p.) following a train of action potentials, occasionally reduced orthodromically evoked p.s.p.s, and had no effect on the width or maximum rate of rise or fall of the action potential. 8. It is concluded that cholinergic inhibition of pyramidal neurones is mediated through a rapid muscarinic excitation of non-pyramidal cells, resulting in the release D. A. McCORMICK AND D. A. PRINCE of GABA. In pyramidal cells ACh causes a relatively slow blockade of both a voltage-dependent hyperpolarizing conductance (M-current) which is most active at depolarized membrane potentials, and the Ca2+-activated K+ conductance underlying the a.h.p. These post-synaptic actions of ACh result in a potentiated response to depolarizing inputs with little or no change in Vm or responses to hyperpolarizing inputs. The ability of ACh to cause the release of GABA may allow the cholinergic system to regulate cortical inhibition also.},
